value.value: A cell phenotype in which DNA is broken into small fragments when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0. Use 'fragmented DNA' (FYPO:0000160) or one of its descendants if DNA was detected using a method that can resolve molecule sizes (e.g. gel electrophoresis) or detect DNA ends (e.g. TUNEL assay). Otherwise, consider using 'fragmented nucleus' (FYPO:0001919) or one of its descendants.

label.value: inviable elongated multinucleate vegetative cell with central constriction

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell contains more than one nucleus, is elongated, is inviable, and has an abnormal shape featuring a constriction at the center of the cell, corresponding to the cell division site. In a cell with this phenotype, the diameter at the ends may be much greater than in wild-type cells. Septal material may accumulate in patches at the cell surface, but no septum forms.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitosis is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the actomyosin contractile ring is absent from the cell.

definition.value: In the absence of filamentous actin, a ring structure may form, but is not considered a contractile ring.

value.value: A cytokinesis phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the assembly and distribution of actin filaments and associated proteins does not occur, resulting in the failure to form an actomyosin contractile ring.

definition.value: Note that a ring structure may form without filamentous actin, but a ring lacking F-actin is not considered a contractile ring.

value.value: A cytokinesis phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the assembly and distribution of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments does not occur.
A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells do not contain filamentous actin structures, such as cortical patches or dots, or rings.
Auxotrophy in which a cell is unable to synthesize uracil, and therefore requires uracil in the medium for vegetative cell growth.

A cellular process phenotype in which cellular membrane organization is abnormal. Cellular membrane organization results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a lipid bilayer membrane, such as the plasma membrane or an organelle membrane.

label.value: abnormal membrane organization during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cellular membrane organization is abnormal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate measured in a cell differs from normal.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing actinomycin D.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the switch from the monopolar to bipolar mode of cell growth (new end take-off; NETO) begins earlier than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the switch from the monopolar to bipolar mode of cell growth (new end take-off; NETO) does not occur.

label.value: monopolar actin cortical patch localization during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin cortical patches are localized to only one end of a cell.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing calcium ions.

label.value: normal growth during cellular response to osmotic stress

value.value: A cell population growth phenotype in which vegetative cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) during a cellular response to osmotic stress.

label.value: normal growth during cellular response to high osmolarity

value.value: A cell population growth phenotype in which vegetative cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) during a cellular response to high osmolarity.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing cisplatin.

A cell cycle phenotype that affects or involves the normal or abnormal occurrence of cell cycle arrest. In cell cycle arrest, progression through the cell cycle is halted during one of the normal phases (G1, S, G2, or M).

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: normally arrested mitotic cell cycle progression

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic cell cycle progression is arrested under conditions where arrest normally occurs.

label.value: abnormal occurrence of normal mitotic cell cycle arrest

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a mitotic cell cycle arrest that normally occurs is abnormal (does not occur, or occurs abnormally).

label.value: normal cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested normally at the mitotic G2/M phase transition when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest in mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested in any part of interphase, under conditions where arrest is not a normal occurrence.

definition.value: Use this term for terminal arrest. If arrest is transient, consider using 'delayed cell cycle phase transition' (FYPO:0000409) or one of its more specific descendants.

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of canavanine than normal.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing dithiothreitol.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites of single-strand breaks in DNA is greater than normal.

definition.value: Because Rad22 often accumulates at double-strand breaks, consider also annotating to 'increased number of Rad52 foci during vegetative growth' (FYPO:0000972).

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of camptothecin than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which double-strand break repair is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of tunicamycin than normal.

label.value: increased cell wall thickness during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the fungal-type cell wall is thicker than normal.

label.value: delaminated cell wall during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the fungal-type cell wall is delaminated, i.e. one or more of its layers peels off.

label.value: normal growth during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell population growth phenotype in which vegetative cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) during a cellular response to salt stress.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins occurs to a greater extent than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of thiamine diphosphokinase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of thiamine diphosphokinase activity is decreased.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of thiamine measured in a cell is higher than normal.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, single or double cell division

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell of normal morphology that undergoes one or two rounds of cell division, and then dies.
A biological process phenotype in which the observed mating efficiency, as determined by counting zygotes, asci, and sometimes spores, is higher than normal.

definition.value: Note that mating efficiency is often measured by counting zygotes plus asci, sometimes also including spores, so a change in measured mating efficiency may reflect a change in conjugation frequency (see FYPO:0000031 and its descendants), a change in sporulation (see FYPO:0000121 and its descendants), or both. For this reason, this term is not a child of 'mating phenotype' (FYPO:0000031).

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of acid phosphatase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of acid phosphatase activity is decreased.
A cellular process phenotype in which cells enter mitosis earlier, relative to cell size or DNA integrity checkpoint status, than normal.

definition.value: Use this term for any experiments that detect early mitosis by any criteria. If you have measured CDK activity or calculated the transition point, also consider using 'premature mitotic G2/M transition' (FYPO:0002516). Also consider annotating to 'viable small vegetative cell' (FYPO:0000648), if mitosis takes place when cells are smaller than normal.

value.value: An inviable phenotype in which a cell enters mitosis when smaller than wild type, and then septates to give rise to a cut phenotype. In a cut phenotype, a cell undergoes septation despite abnormal mitosis such that the septum physically divides the nucleus into two parts.

An inviable phenotype in which a cell enters mitosis at the same size as wild type, and then septates to give rise to a cut phenotype. In a cut phenotype, a cell undergoes septation despite abnormal mitosis such that the septum physically divides the nucleus into two parts.

An inviable phenotype in which a cell enters mitosis when longer than wild type, and then septates to give rise to a cut phenotype. In a cut phenotype, a cell undergoes septation despite abnormal mitosis such that the septum physically divides the nucleus into two parts.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: cut following normal mitotic chromosome condensation

value.value: An inviable phenotype in which a cell enters mitosis normally, in that the spindle forms normally and chromosomes condense normally, but then undergoes septation despite abnormal chromosome segregation, giving rise to a cut phenotype.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which L-arginine import into the cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cellular process phenotype in which the import of one or more amino acids into the cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype in which the import of one or more amino acids into the cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: abnormal glutamate import during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of glutamate into the cell is abnormal in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.
